<h3 id="doc-color-scheme">Color Scheme</h3>
<p>You can use theme-based prefixes to apply different text colors based
on the active color mode (<code>dark:</code> or
<code>light:</code>).</p>
<h4 id="doc-example-1">Example</h4>
<pre class="html"><code>&lt;p class=&quot;light:color-red dark:color-blue&quot;&gt;Red in light mode and blue in dark mode.&lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>
<h4 id="doc-output-1">Output</h4>
<p class="light:color-red dark:color-blue">
Red in light mode and blue in dark mode.
</p>
<h4 id="doc-notes-2">Notes</h4>
<ul>
<li>These prefixes can be combined with hover and focus states, like
<code>dark:hover:color-green-300</code>.</li>
<li>Omitting the prefix applies the color in all modes.</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3 id="doc-hover">Hover</h3>
<p>Use the <code>hover:</code> prefix to apply a text color when the
user hovers over an element.</p>
<h4 id="doc-syntax-1">Syntax</h4>
<pre class="css"><code>hover:color-[name]-[shade]</code></pre>
<ul>
<li>Triggers the text color change <strong>on hover</strong></li>
<li>Can be combined with other variants like <code>dark:</code> or
<code>light:</code></li>
</ul>
<h4 id="doc-example-2">Example</h4>
<pre class="html"><code>&lt;p class=&quot;hover:color-blue-500&quot;&gt;
  Hover over this text to turn it blue.
&lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>
<h4 id="doc-output-2">Output</h4>
<p class="hover:color-blue-500">
Hover over this text to turn it blue.
</p>
